dataIdInfo.idPurp: Belize combined Road network have been developed as part of exposure database for the transportation infrastructure, drainage and flood mitigation structures associated with the transportation system, and for public buildings in Belize (Global Facility for Disaster Reduction and Recovery (GFDRR) / World Bank Financed Project)
dataIdInfo.idAbs: This dataset contains road feature as polyline for Belize. The RMSI project team received the input data files from MoWT (Ministry of Work and Transport) in different formats like, the surveyed road data as AutoCAD drawing (.dwg) for different districts (except Toledo), ESRI Shape files (.shp) for the entire country, and excel file (.xls) containing different road attributes. Based on the Unique Road ID available attributes from survey detail excel sheet are attached to corresponding shape files. Wherever the survey data from MoWT is not available, 5 m resolotion RapidEye imagery has been used to fill the gaps. Parts of the road data is to be modified based on field survey being performed by the survey team.

searchKeys.keyword: Belize Road Layer containing Surveyed (2013) and Unsurveyed Road segments

idPoC.rpOrgName: Ministry of Works and Transport (MoWT), Belize

dataIdInfo.idCredit: RMSI, MOW, WorldBank, Global Facility for Disaster Reduction and Recovery (GFDRR)

dataLineage.statement: The surveyed road segments selected for the field survey have been captured as polyline using high resolution Trimble GeoExplorer 3000 GPS. In addition, the RMSI project team received the input data files from MoWT (Ministry of Work and Transport) in different formats like, the surveyed road data as AutoCAD drawing (.dwg) for different districts (except Toledo), ESRI Shape files (.shp) for the entire country, and excel file (.xls) containing different road attributes. Based on the Unique Road ID available attributes from survey detail excel sheet are attached to corresponding shape files. Wherever the survey data from MoWT is not available, 5 m resolotion RapidEye imagery has been used to fill the gaps. Parts of the road data is to be modified based on field survey being performed by the survey team.

prcStep.stepDesc:
As per the scope of the study, the road segments selected for the field survey have been captured as polyline using high resolution Trimble GeoExplorer 3000 GPS device in back and forth direction for each road segments. In the next step, the road polylines captured are processed using GIS tools to generate the road centerline data with necessary topological corrections. The road centerline data prepared is then segmented using the start and end mile information of the MoWT and their available attributes has been attached in this road centerline.
Results were verified using georeferenced 5 m resolution RapidEye Imagery (2011 and 2012 dates) + online high resolution imagery available as "basemap" in ArcGis. The same sources were used to verify the MOWT road autocad data as well as used to fill in gaps.
prcStep.stepRat: Provide a road baseline dataset for Belize

dqReport.measDesc: All logical quality checks (QA/QC) applied in this data including duplicate features, incorrect intersections, snapping tolerance etc. to ensure desired quality
This dataset contains all the major roads of Belize. As per the scope of the study, the road segments selected for field survey have been captured using high-resolution GPS device.

This spatial location has been captured during the field survey and existing attribute information collected from the Ministry of Works and Transport (MoWT), Belize has been verified during the field survey.
The geographic locations were reflected less than 2.5m resolution and the survey roads have been topologically cleaned to improve data quality.

All roads with a number can be assumed to be "owned" by the Ministry of Works, but roads within protected areas typically fall under the jurisdiction of the Forest Department. Roads within municipalities are owned by the municipality apart from the through roads (Highways).

Consts.useLimit: Surveyed roads are based on GPS recordings but the resulting GIS file has not been checked in the field and some errors may exists. The attempt was to have an accuracy level of 4-5 meters, and this has been confirmed based on remote sensed data only. As a result the preferred scale should not be finer than 1.10.000
